50957	0	0	0	108	CONF	72	0	0	175	0	0	0	0	0	0	0	0	14500	0	-2518	0	true	0	0	0	0	0	0	153	0	0	0	132	130	0	0	0	0	OREO PROPERTY INCOME			REPOSSESSED PROPERTY EXPENSE						CAPITL CONTRIUBTUION FROM PARENT HOLDING COMPAN		PURCHASE ACCOUNT ADJUSTMENTS		1. On April 30, 2010, all of the outstanding common stock of 1st Financial Bank was acquired by Aslin Group, Inc. in exchange for a cash payment of $1. Concurrent with the acquisition, 1st Financial Bank was renamed Alterra Bank (the Bank). At that date, the Bank's liabilities exceeded its assets by $3,012,267. The acquisition was accounted for under the provisions of FASB ASC 805 (SFAS 141R. Business Combinations). Accordingly, the Bank adjusted the carrying values of the acquired tangible and identifiable intangible assets and the assumed liabilities to their estimated fair values. 2. In addition, the Bank recorded goodwill of $2,631,117. FASB ASC 805 allows a measurement period of up to one year to adjust initial fair value estimates as an additional information regarding such fair values as of the acquisition date becomes available. 3. Concurrent with the acquisition of the Bank, Aslin Group, Inc. contributed additional cash capital of $12,500,000 to the Bank, which represents the opening shareholders equity balance as of April 30, 2010. 4. As a result of the application of FASB ASC 805 and ASC 310-30, the April 30, 2010 balance sheet for Alterra Bank did not include an allowance for loan losses. The current provision and allowance for loan losses reflected as of December 31 is related to the growth in the loan portfolio since the acquisition. 5. Income reported in Schedules RI represents income since the acquisition date.

Error involves push down accounting requirements of ESOP debt reflected on parent holding company financial statements, but not previously reflected on bank statements. The relevant accounting principles as applied to this situation are technical, unclear and open to interpretation. Bank management became aware of the error in September 2010 and took immediate steps to avoid material deviations in bank equity capital from prior reporting periods via a corresponding contribution of equity from the parent holding company (See Schedule RI-A #11 and Schedule RI-E #5.a). Organizational structure and resources of parent holding company are such that these steps could and would have been taken earlier had bank management been earlier aware of the error. The $3.8 million net gain of sales of securities is included on Schedule RI, Line 6b. The $3.6 million Loss on extinguishment of Debt is included in Schedule RI, Line 7d (Other Non-Interest Expense) and further detailed on Schedule RIE, Line 2l. In 2010, Peoples recognized write-downs on Other Real Estate Owned and 3 commercial real estate loans being held-for-sale, due to a decline in property values. The income statement, balance sheet and Tier 1 Capital are reviewed quarterly by the Board. In April 2010, the Bank increased its liquidity by $5M. In Dec 2010, the bank signed an agreement with management of Barrett Associates, a subsidiary, to sell substantially all assets and liabilities of Barrett. The agreement provides for future closing upon regulatory and other approvals. As of 12/31/10, the related assets and liabilities have been written down to the $4.499M agreement value and were reclassified to "other net assets subject to transfer agreement", resulting in a $15.4M operating charge. The $4.499M goodwill and intangible asset amounts will continue to be disallowed until the consideration is paid. The immediate regulatory capital impact is negligible; subsequent closing and receipts of contingent consideration will increase regulatory capital.
